er for Neurological Disease Research, University of Georgia, Athens, GA 30602, USA; Department of Physiology and Pharmacology, College of Veterinary Medicine, University of Georgia, Athens, GA 30602, USA.\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41172985/?fc=None&amp;ff=20251101161538&amp;v=2.18.0.post22+67771e2#full-view-affiliation-1\">\n                1\n              </a></sup><span>, </span></span><span><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=Anantharam+V&amp;cauthor_id=41172985\">Vellareddy Anantharam</a><sup><span> </span><a target=\"_blank\" title=\"Isakson Center for Neurological Disease Research, University of Georgia, Athens, GA 30602, USA; Department of Physiology and Pharmacology, College of Veterinary Medicine, University of Georgia, Athens, GA 30602, USA.\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41172985/?fc=None&amp;ff=20251101161538&amp;v=2.18.0.post22+67771e2#full-view-affiliation-1\">\n                1\n              </a></sup><span>, </span></span><span><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=Kanthasamy+A&amp;cauthor_id=41172985\">Arthi Kanthasamy</a><sup><span> </span><a target=\"_blank\" title=\"Isakson Center for Neurological Disease Research, University of Georgia, Athens, GA 30602, USA; Department of Physiology and Pharmacology, College of Veterinary Medicine, University of Georgia, Athens, GA 30602, USA.\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41172985/?fc=None&amp;ff=20251101161538&amp;v=2.18.0.post22+67771e2#full-view-affiliation-1\">\n                1\n              </a></sup><span>, </span></span><span><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=Mishra+A&amp;cauthor_id=41172985\">Aditya Mishra</a><sup><span> </span><a target=\"_blank\" title=\"Department of Statistics, Franklin College of Arts and Sciences, University of Georgia, Athens, GA 30602, USA.\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41172985/?fc=None&amp;ff=20251101161538&amp;v=2.18.0.post22+67771e2#full-view-affiliation-6\">\n                6\n              </a></sup><span>, </span></span><span><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=Allenspach+K&amp;cauthor_id=41172985\">Karin Allenspach</a><sup><span> </span><a target=\"_blank\" title=\"Department of Pathology, College of Veterinary Medicine, University of Georgia, Athens, GA 30602, USA.\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41172985/?fc=None&amp;ff=20251101161538&amp;v=2.18.0.post22+67771e2#full-view-affiliation-7\">\n                7\n              </a></sup><span>, </span></span><span><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=Mochel+J&amp;cauthor_id=41172985\">Jonathan Mochel</a><sup><span> </span><a target=\"_blank\" title=\"Department of Pathology, College of Veterinary Medicine, University of Georgia, Athens, GA 30602, USA.\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41172985/?fc=None&amp;ff=20251101161538&amp;v=2.18.0.post22+67771e2#full-view-affiliation-7\">\n                7\n              </a></sup><span>, </span></span><span><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=Phillips+GJ&amp;cauthor_id=41172985\">Gregory J Phillips</a><sup><span> </span><a target=\"_blank\" title=\"Isakson Center for Neurological Disease Research, University of Georgia, Athens, GA 30602, USA; Department of Infectious Diseases, College of Veterinary Medicine, University of Georgia, Athens, GA 30602, USA.\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41172985/?fc=None&amp;ff=20251101161538&amp;v=2.18.0.post22+67771e2#full-view-affiliation-5\">\n                5\n              </a></sup><span>, </span></span><span><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=Kanthasamy+AG&amp;cauthor_id=41172985\">Anumantha G Kanthasamy</a><sup><span> </span><a target=\"_blank\" title=\"Isakson Center for Neurological Disease Research, University of Georgia, Athens, GA 30602, USA; Department of Physiology and Pharmacology, College of Veterinary Medicine, University of Georgia, Athens, GA 30602, USA. Electronic address: anumantha.kanthasamy@uga.edu.\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41172985/?fc=None&amp;ff=20251101161538&amp;v=2.18.0.post22+67771e2#full-view-affiliation-8\">\n                8\n              </a></sup></span>\n  </p></div>\n          <p>\n    Affiliations\n</p>\n    <ul>\n        <li>\n          <span>\n  <span>\n      PMID:\n  </span>\n    <strong>41172985</strong>\n</span>\n        </li>\n        <li>\n          <span>\n  <span>\n      DOI:\n  </span>\n    <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://doi.org/10.1016/j.chom.2025.10.005\">\n      10.1016/j.chom.2025.10.005\n    </a>\n</span>\n        </li>\n    </ul>\n        <p>\n  Item in Clipboard\n</p>\n      </div>\n      <div>\n<h2>\n  Bioengineered gut bacterium synthesizing levodopa alleviates motor deficits in models of Parkinson's disease\n</h2>\n<p><span>\n        <span><span>Piyush Padhi</span><span> et al.</span></span>\n  </span>\n      <span>\n        Cell Host Microbe<span>.</span>\n      </span>\n        <span>\n          2025<span>.</span>\n        </span>\n</p>\n      </div>\n  <div>\n      <h2>\n        Abstract\n      </h2>\n            <p>\n      L-3,4-Dihydroxyphenylalanine (L-DOPA), synthesized from L-tyrosine, is a direct precursor to dopamine. L-DOPA is the gold-standard treatment for Parkinson's disease (PD), given orally alongside decarboxylase inhibitors (e.g., benserazide) to enhance bioavailability. However, its chronic daily pulsatile-like delivery is associated with complications. Herein, we show the construction and in vivo efficacy of a programmable, titratable, genetically engineered E. coli Nissle 1917 system (EcN<sub>L-DOPA</sub>) that continuously synthesizes L-DOPA from L-tyrosine for systemic distribution. Oral administration of EcN<sub>L-DOPA</sub> with benserazide maintains therapeutic plasma L-DOPA concentrations and increases brain dopamine levels. EcN<sub>L-DOPA</sub> improves motor performance and limits depressive-like behaviors without adverse side effects in healthy mice, Parkinsonian mice, and canine models. Simulated physiological models from pharmacokinetic and pharmacodynamic studies in canines demonstrate the translational feasibility of this biotherapeutic system for potential human studies. This work lays the groundwork for EcN<sub>L-DOPA</sub> as a continuous, non-invasive microbial drug delivery platform for PD and chronic neurological diseases.\n    </p>\n    <p>\n        <strong>\n          Keywords:\n        </strong>\n      Canine model; E. coli Nissle 1917; MitoPark; Parkinson’s disease; bacterial therapeutics; drug delivery; engineered live biotherapeutics; gut microbiome; levodopa; synthetic biology.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <p>\n    Copyright © 2025 The Authors. Published by Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n  <a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/disclaimer/\" target=\"_blank\">PubMed Disclaimer</a>\n</p>\n  <div>\n    <h2>\n      Conflict of interest statement\n    </h2>\n    <p>Declaration of interests P.P., A.G.K., and V.A. hold equity interests in Probiome Therapeutics. This arrangement was reviewed and approved by the University of Georgia. The core technology is embodied in US Patent 11,576,883 and US Patent Applications Numbers 18/153,739, 17/304,444, and 18/455,205.</p>\n  </div>\n  </div>",
